  "prompt": "How do calculate the gear ratio?",
  "response": "To calculate the gear ratio, you need to determine the number of teeth on the gears involved in the system. The gear ratio is calculated using the following formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driven Gear}}{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driving Gear}}\n\\]\n\n### Steps to Calculate Gear Ratio:\n\n1. **Identify the Gears**: Determine which gear is the driving gear (the gear that is supplying the power) and which is the driven gear (the gear being turned).\n\n2. **Count the Teeth**: Count the number of teeth on each gear:\n   - Let \\( T_d \\) be the number of teeth on the driven gear.\n   - Let \\( T_r \\) be the number of teeth on the driving gear.\n\n3. **Apply the Formula**: Substitute the number of teeth into the formula:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{T_d}{T_r}\n   \\]\n\n### Example:\n\nIf the driving gear has 10 teeth and the driven gear has 30 teeth, the gear ratio is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{30}{10} = 3\n\\]\n\nThis means for every 1 turn of the driving gear, the driven gear will complete approximately \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\) of a turn.\n\n### Important Note:\n- A gear ratio greater than 1 indicates a speed reduction (i.e., the driven gear will turn slower than the driving gear).\n- A gear ratio less than 1 indicates that the driven gear will turn faster than the driving gear. \n\n### In Summary:\nThe gear ratio is a simple calculation based on the number of teeth on the involved gears and is crucial for understanding mechanical advantage, torque, and rotational speed in gear systems.",
